---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ProductCard from '../../components/ProductCard.astro';
import products from '../../../data/products.json';

const solo = products.find(p => p.id === 'focusrite-scarlett-solo-4th-gen')!;
const twoI2 = products.find(p => p.id === 'focusrite-scarlett-2i2-4th-gen')!;
---

<Layout
  title="What Audio Interface Do I Need? (2026) — HomeRecordingGear"
  description="What audio interface do you actually need as a beginner? Plain answer, no jargon."
>
  <article class="space-y-8">
    <header class="space-y-3">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide font-medium">Guide</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">What Audio Interface Do I Actually Need?</h1>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-lg">
        An audio interface converts your microphone's signal into something your computer understands.
        Here's whether you need one and which one to get.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-5 space-y-1">
      <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Do you need one at all?</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700">
        Only if you're using an XLR microphone. USB mics connect directly to your computer — no interface needed.
        If you're considering a USB mic, <a href="/vs/usb-vs-xlr-microphone-beginners" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">read this first</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">What does an interface actually do?</h2>
      <p>
        Your XLR mic outputs an analog signal. Your computer's built-in audio input (if it has one at all)
        is designed for consumer headphone-level signals, not microphone signals. An interface:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
        <li>Amplifies the mic signal with a clean preamp</li>
        <li>Converts analog to digital (ADC) at professional quality</li>
        <li>Handles the phantom power that condenser mics need</li>
        <li>Gives you a headphone output with zero-latency monitoring</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Which interface do beginners need?</h2>
      <p>
        For one mic at a time: the <strong>Focusrite Scarlett Solo</strong>. It's the most recommended
        beginner interface for a reason — reliable, clean-sounding, works on Mac and Windows,
        and comes with a software bundle (Ableton Live Lite, plugins) worth more than the interface itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        For two simultaneous inputs (guitar + mic, two people): the <strong>Scarlett 2i2</strong>.
        Same preamp quality, two inputs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <ProductCard
          name={solo.name}
          price={solo.price}
          rating={solo.rating}
          reviewCount={solo.review_count}
          affiliateUrl={solo.affiliate_url}
          badge="For one mic"
          description="1 XLR + 1 instrument input. The standard beginner interface."
        />
        <ProductCard
          name={twoI2.name}
          price={twoI2.price}
          rating={twoI2.rating}
          reviewCount={twoI2.review_count}
          affiliateUrl={twoI2.affiliate_url}
          badge="For two inputs"
          description="2 XLR/instrument inputs. Record guitar and vocals simultaneously."
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">What about the really cheap interfaces?</h2>
      <p>
        Interfaces under $50 from brands you've never heard of tend to have one or more of these problems:
        driver issues after macOS updates, too much background noise in the preamp, flaky build quality,
        or latency that makes monitoring painful. The Scarlett costs more but just works, and you won't
        be googling driver fixes at 11pm.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Related</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-1">
        <li><a href="/vs/focusrite-scarlett-solo-vs-2i2" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">Focusrite Scarlett Solo vs 2i2 — full comparison →</a></li>
        <li><a href="/vs/usb-vs-xlr-microphone-beginners" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">USB vs XLR: which should beginners get? →</a></li>
        <li><a href="/best/audio-interfaces-for-beginners" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">Best audio interfaces for beginners →</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
